The following index definition examples use collections in the
[sample data sets](available-sample-datasets). After you
[Load Sample Data Into Atlas](load-sample-data), you can use the
Visual Editor or JSON (Javascript Object Notation) Editor to configure
these indexes. After you select your preferred configuration method,
select the database and collection, and refine your index to add field
mappings.

Basic Example

The following index definition indexes string values in the
`title` field as the MongoDB Search `string` type:

Visual Editor

- In the Add Field Mapping window, select
  title from the Field Name
  dropdown.

- Click the Data Type dropdown and select
  String.

- Review the default settings for the String
  Properties.

- Click Add.

JSON Editor

Replace the default index definition with the following index
definition.

```json
{
  "mappings": {
    "dynamic": false,
    "fields": {
      "title": {
        "type": "string"
      }
    }
  }
}

```

Multi Example

The following index definition for the `sample_mflix.movies`
collection in the [sample data sets](available-sample-datasets)
indexes the `title` field with string values. It also specifies the
analyzers [Language awareness](ref-language-analyzers) and
[Language awareness](ref-language-analyzers) as alternate analyzers for
the `title` field, and the `stableTfl` similarity algorithm as an
alternate similarity algorithm.

Visual Editor

> **Note:** To confgure the `similarity.type` property, you must use the
> JSON (Javascript Object Notation) Editor.

- In the Add Field Mapping window, select
  title from the Field Name
  dropdown.

- Click the Data Type dropdown and select
  String.

- Review the default settings for the String
  Properties.

- Click Add Multi Field, enter `english` in
  the Multi Field Name field, and configure the
  following Multi Field Properties:

  | Index Analyzer  | Select lucene.english under lucene.language. |
  | --------------- | -------------------------------------------- |
  | Search Analyzer | Select lucene.english under lucene.language. |

- Click Add Another Multi Field, enter
  `french` in the Multi Field Name field, and
  configure the following Multi Field Properties:

  | Index Analyzer  | Select lucene.french under lucene.language.  |
  | --------------- | -------------------------------------------- |
  | Search Analyzer | Select lucene.french under lucene. language. |

- Click Add.

JSON Editor

Replace the default index definition with the following index
definition.

```json
{
  "mappings": {
    "dynamic": false,
    "fields": {
      "title": {
        "type": "string",
        "multi": {
          "english": {
            "type": "string",
            "analyzer": "lucene.english"
          },
          "french": {
            "type": "string",
            "analyzer": "lucene.french"
          },
          "stableSimilarity": {
            "type": "string",
            "similarity": { "type": "stableTfl"}
          }
        }
      }
    }
  }
}

```
